Thus, the general scattering amplitude is a function of $(s, t,\alpha,\beta,\gamma,\delta)$ while the forward, crossing-symmetric amplitude is a function of $(s,\alpha,\beta)$. In order to maintain crossing symmetry simultaneously with the forward limit, we must assume linear polarizations for the external states \cite{us}, which means that the vectors $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are real. 

